Tutorial 2 - Building The Library
Tutorial

Tutorial 2 - Building The Library

6 steps

NOTE: Getting rewards from this quest is over as it was only applicable on the Earn app when it was part of a campaign. Therefore, submissions are not reviewed or are disabled. However, you are highly encouraged to still complete the quest to practice your understanding.

Now that we know a bit more about APIs, lets begin writing our API library in this tutorial

The focus when writing our API library is more exploratory than a full implementation. This is to let you know what processes a typical developer does when experimenting with an API. You will also learn new terminologies such as serialisation and deserialisation.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Check out the Rust Pathway. This quest requires you to have some basic knowledge of Rusts syntax and semantics.

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Understand Rust library structure
  • Understand the concept of (De)Serialisation
  • Use serde-rs and serde-json to (de)serialise JSON
  • Use reqwest to communicate with APIs

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Initialising a new project

    To create a new project, head out to your terminal emulator and choose a specific directory where your new project resides. Then run the following command below

    cargo new --lib endoflife

    The video below should show you how its all done from creating a project to adding the dependencies.

    The reason why we add these dependencies will be discussed starting from Step 2 until Step 4.

  • Step 2: What is Serialising and Deserialising

    Before we begin, we need to understand what the terms serialising and deserializing means.

    Serialising is the process of converting data structures into human readable formats such as JSON, CSV, and even text!

    The opposite of serialising is deserialising. Its a process of converting raw data into machine code or objects that are usually data structures that attempt to map the data based on a specified format. For example, lets take this piece of JSON text

    {
  "name": "Emily",
  "age": 20,
  "children": ["Roxanne", "Alexia"]
}
    JSON

    The close equivalent mapping of this data when its deserialized in a Rust data structure is

    struct Person {
    name: String,
    age: u64,
    children: Option<Vec<String>>, // Person might not have any children at all
}
    Rust

    But how do we do this? Its possible that we could write our own parser for this. But sometimes, its better for us to not reinvent the wheel by using an existing library which will be discussed in the next step.

  • Step 3: Introducing serde-rs

    To ease the difficulties of serialising and deserialising, we will use serde-rs or just serde. This crate library provides a template for writing (de)serialisation libraries for other data formats.

    The data format we are going to (de)serialise is JSON since the https://endoflife.date API uses that format as seen from the .json extension. There is already a Rust library using serde that helps us (de)serialise JSON that is serde-json.

    Do not be confused when you see (de)serialisation because usually, when libraries can serialise, that also means they can deserialise. This also explains the name serialisation/deserialisation of the crate library. Now, lets continue.

    We can begin adding these dependencies into our project by running the following command

    cargo add serde -F derive
cargo add serde-json

    We included the derive feature in serde so that we can lessen the boilerplate code when writing the data structures that map the data. The derive feature provides the derive attribute which allows us to inherit the traits Serializer and Deserializer from serde.

  • Step 4: Mapping and Mirroring Data with serde-rs

    Now that we know some of the ideas of serde, we can begin (de)serialising the data from the API. Lets attempt to focus on the Rust releases in the https://endoflife.date API. Our API endpoint would be focusing on the single release cycle or a single version and its release cycle.

    For this, we will focus on version 1.78 of the Rust release cycles. The API endpoint URL would be https://endoflife.date/api/rust/1.78.json. Feel free to use cURL or Postman for this to get the JSON response string.

    Update: As of writing, Rust has recently released version 1.79 so outputs in the video and your output might look a bit different. Rest assured, this won't impact your submissions since we are going to write tests to foolproof our library. If you want to test out the new API endpoint, you can use https://endoflife.date/api/rust/1.79.json.

    Full videos of how it was done can be found below. Feel free to increase or decrease the speed of the videos. But be careful since youll need to follow along with the videos and copy all the code from the videos as they will be needed for this quest.

    Video Part 1 - Layouting the project (timestamped)

    Video summary

    We began by layouting the project and importing the serde into the rust module. Next, we write our struct that closely resembles the JSON string data. Lastly, we print the data into the JSON string.

    Video Part 2 - Experimenting

    Video summary

    In this video, we use the if-let syntax instead of unwrapping to simulate error-handling.

    Video Part 3 - Serialising back to JSON String

    Video Summary

    We experimented to see if the JSON string produced by serialising the data structure or object is similar. However, we need to add test cases for this to support that what we serialise is also what we deserialised.

    Additional Video with Explanation

    Something that isn't mentioned in the video is that we are also attempting to map the types associated with the field names. For example, eol here is set to bool because our JSON string uses the false directive. releaseDate also looks like a date but for now we use an Option<String> type. This is to ensure that if releaseDate is empty, it will deserialise to the None variant of the Option enum.

    After following the instructions in the videos, lets proceed to the next step!

  • Step 5: Communicate with the API using reqwest

    Head to your project and run the command below in your terminal

    cargo add reqwest -F blocking

    This will add reqwest as one of your dependencies with blocking feature. We dont want to step into async yet as its not needed. We also avoided adding json feature to get the idea of how we deserialise our response.

    In src/lib.rs, append the line pub mod request; . Make sure it's there.

    Next, head to your project and create the file src/request.rs. The first line is our constant HEADER.

    const HEADER: &str = "application/json";
    Rust

    Receiving and Handling the Response

    Finally, add the following code snippet to your file src/request.rs.

    use std::error::Error;
use crate::rust::RustSingleCycle;
use reqwest::{ self, blocking::Client, header::ACCEPT };

pub fn api_request_single_rust_cycle(
    rust_version: &str
) -> Result<RustSingleCycle, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let request_string: String = format!("https://endoflife.date/api/rust/{}.json", rust_version);
    let client = Client::new();
    let body = client.get(request_string).header(ACCEPT, HEADER).send()?.bytes()?.to_vec();
    let response = unsafe { String::from_utf8_unchecked(body) };
    let deserialised_response = serde_json::from_str::<RustSingleCycle>(&response)?;
    Ok(deserialised_response)
}
    Rust

    Here is a video explaining how this code works.

  • Step 6: Lets Ace It! Preparing Your Submissions!

    Finally! We are done with writing our first function for our API library!

    Now, to make sure you successfully complete this quest, there is 1 deliverable that is required - a screenshot.

    But before we take a screenshot, put this code snippet to your file src/request.rs

    pub fn api_request_all_rust_cycles() -> Result<Vec<RustSingleCycle>, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let request_string: &str = "https://endoflife.date/api/rust.json";

    // Builds the client request
    let client = Client::new();

    // Our response body
    let body = client.get(request_string).header(ACCEPT, HEADER).send()?.bytes()?.to_vec();

    // Our response string
    let response = unsafe { String::from_utf8_unchecked(body) };
    let deserialised_response: Vec<RustSingleCycle> = serde_json::from_str(&response)?;
    Ok(deserialised_response)
}
    Rust

    Next, replace all the contents of your main.rs file with

    use endoflife::request::api_request_all_rust_cycles;

fn main() {
    let _all_cycles = api_request_all_rust_cycles().unwrap();
}
    Rust

    Then run the following command

    RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo run

    If there is a runtime failure, dont worry, its part of the campaign and youll still pass! However, the expected output should be similar to the sample screenshot, specifically, the blue box in the image that is annotated with Terminal Output.

    Your screenshot should show:

    • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS)
    • a compiler error message with backtrace enabled as terminal output
    • your entire main.rs
    • your file explorer

    Refer to the image if you are unsure. If the image is too small, right click on the image and press on 'Open Image in New Tab'.

    When labelling your screenshot, make sure to follow the format provided C28_Q2_yourusername.png.

    In the event that your screen is not wide enough to accommodate multiple windows side by side, you may take the screenshots separately and then merge them into one image.

    You can use any editing tool for that e.g. using Powerpoint to merge them on Windows, using Preview on MacOS/OSX or using Imagemagick on Linux e.g. running the following command

    convert image23.png image18.png +append C28_Q2_yourusername.png

    Or use a web tool such as https://www.adobe.com/express/feature/image/combine.
